<DOC><DOCNO> AP880716-0053 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-16-88 0836EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a PM-WeatherpageWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0485endearlyintheafternoon07-16 0500</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0485,0507</SECOND><BYLINE>Thunderstorms Swirl Over Much Of The Nation</BYLINE><NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, `In Kansas ...' to RESTORE dropped`winds.' Minneapolis, Kan., is cq.</NOTE><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Thunderstorms rumbled over much of the nation today after hot,moist and unstable air from the Gulf of Mexico clashed with a coldfront from Kansas to Wisconsin to whip up tornadoes, damagingwinds, hail and rain.   In Nebraska, three tornadoes were reported in the Omaha andCouncil Bluffs areas Friday, damaging more than 100 homes andflipping railroad cars. Trees and power lines were damaged ordowned in Omaha.   In Kansas, the same line of thunderstorms spawned a tornado nearWakefield; caused 55 to 60 mph winds at Abilene; produced damagingwinds at Minneapolis, and blasted Ellsworth with 1}-inch hail.   Thunderstorms swirling through Wisconsin and Minnesota rippeddown trees and brought hail nearly 2 inches in diameter.Thunderstorms also produced damaging winds in portions of Indianaand Michigan.   In lower Michigan, Kent County was pummeled by 1{-inch hail. Abuilding roof was destroyed and several trees were damaged in EmmetCounty.   In Florida, tornadoes touched down at Tarpon Springs, wherethere was damage to several unoccupied trailer homes. Two tornadoeswere reported near Palatka.   Today's forecast called for rain and thunderstorms from northernand central New England across inland New York, through Florida andthe central Gulf of Mexico coast; showers and thunderstormsscattered over northern Indiana and northern Illinois, andgenerally sunny weather over the rest of the nation.   High temperatures were forecast in the 70s and 80s over northernNew England, inland New York, Michigan, Wisconsin and fromMinnesota across the northern tier of states through Washingtoninto northern Oregon; in the 70s and 80s along the Californiacoast; the upper 90s and 100 degrees from southern West Virginiaacross southern Ohio, Indiana, Illinois, Kentucky, Tennessee,northern Georgia, much of Mississippi, Kansas, central Texas,western Colorado and northern Utah; near 115 degrees through thedesert Southwest, and in the 90s through the rest of the nation.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 49degrees at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 97 degrees atGlendale, Ariz.   Other reports:   _East: Atlanta 81 fair; Boston 67 fair; Buffalo 74 cloudy;Charleston, S.C. 80 foggy; Cincinnati 83 fair; Cleveland 81 cloudy;Detroit 77 cloudy; Miami 78 fair; New York 72 foggy; Philadelphia72 foggy; Pittsburgh 75 partly cloudy; Portland, Maine 61 partlycloudy; Washington 79 fair.   _Central: Bismarck 59 fair; Chicago 85 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth84 fair; Denver 65 fair; Des Moines 75 cloudy; Indianapolis 80hazy; Kansas City 71 cloudy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 77 partly cloudy;Nashville 83 fair; New Orleans 77 fair; St. Louis 85 fair.   _West: Albuquerque 77 partly cloudy; Anchorage 63 partly cloudy;Las Vegas 87 fair; Los Angeles 64 hazy; Phoenix 96 fair; Salt LakeCity 70 fair; San Diego 67 cloudy; San Francisco 58 fair; Seattle57 fair.   _Canada: Montreal 64 partly cloudy; Toronto 73 cloudy.</TEXT></DOC>